Jack Sarfatti (sarfatti@netcom.com) wrote:

: Andre Berthiaume and Giles Brassard of IRO Universite de Montreal, CP 6128,

: Succursale, Montreal, Quebec, Canada H3C 3J7 write:

[ ... deleted ... ]

: ...quantum cryptography provides a technologically feasible oracle-free 
: approach for harnessing quantum physics for computational purposes,,, it 
: mildly challenges the Church-Turing thesis itself...it allows one to achieve

: tasks that are demonstrably impossible when Turing machines are allowed 
: unlimited computing power."

That's a bit different.  Quantum cryptography, AFAIK, allows provably
secure key exchange.  This doesn't necessarily involve any
computational processes at all.  As key exchange does not _require_
computation, how can quantum cryptography have any effect on the
Church-Turing thesis?

Andrew.

